org.apache.beam.runners.flink.translation.wrappers.streaming

Class FlinkGroupAlsoByWindowWrapper<K,VIN,VACC,VOUT>

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, org.apache.flink.streaming.api.operators.OneInputStreamOperator<WindowedValue<KV<K,VIN>>,WindowedValue<KV<K,VOUT>>>, org.apache.flink.streaming.api.operators.StreamOperator<WindowedValue<KV<K,VOUT>>>

    public class FlinkGroupAlsoByWindowWrapper<K,VIN,VACC,VOUT>
extends org.apache.flink.streaming.api.operators.AbstractStreamOperator<WindowedValue<KV<K,VOUT>>>
implements org.apache.flink.streaming.api.operators.OneInputStreamOperator<WindowedValue<KV<K,VIN>>,WindowedValue<KV<K,VOUT>>>
    This class is the key class implementing all the windowing/triggering logic of Apache Beam. To provide full compatibility and support for all the windowing/triggering combinations offered by Beam, we opted for a strategy that uses the SDK's code for doing these operations. See the code in (org.apache.beam.runners.core.GroupAlsoByWindowsDoFn.

    In a nutshell, when the execution arrives to this operator, we expect to have a stream already grouped by key. Each of the elements that enter here, registers a timer (see TimerInternals.setTimer(TimerInternals.TimerData) in the activeTimers. This is essentially a timestamp indicating when to trigger the computation over the window this element belongs to.

    When a watermark arrives, all the registered timers are checked to see which ones are ready to fire (see processWatermark(Watermark)). These are deregistered from the activeTimers list, and are fed into the org.apache.beam.runners.core.GroupAlsoByWindowsDoFn for furhter processing.

                                                                                                                       Combine.KeyedCombineFn<K,VIN,VACC,VOUT> combiner,
                                                                                                                       KvCoder<K,VOUT> outputKvCoder)
        Creates an DataStream where elements are grouped in windows based on the specified windowing strategy. This method assumes that elements are already grouped by key.

        The difference with createForIterable(PipelineOptions, PCollection, KeyedStream) is that this method assumes that a combiner function is provided (see Combine.KeyedCombineFn). A combiner helps at increasing the speed and, in most of the cases, reduce the per-window state.

        Parameters:
        options - the general job configuration options.
        input - the input Dataflow PCollection.
        groupedStreamByKey - the input stream, it is assumed to already be grouped by key.
        combiner - the combiner to be used.
        outputKvCoder - the type of the output values.

        Creates an DataStream where elements are grouped in windows based on the specified windowing strategy. This method assumes that elements are already grouped by key.

        The difference with create(PipelineOptions, PCollection, KeyedStream, Combine.KeyedCombineFn, KvCoder) is that this method assumes no combiner function (see Combine.KeyedCombineFn).

        Parameters:
        options - the general job configuration options.
        input - the input Dataflow PCollection.
        groupedStreamByKey - the input stream, it is assumed to already be grouped by key.
